# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: binary-heap
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] A **binary heap** is a heap data structure that takes the form of a binary tree.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Binary heaps are a common way of implementing priority queues.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Williams in 1964 as a data structure for implementing heapsort.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Heaps where the parent key is greater than or equal to (≥) the child keys are called *max-heaps*; those where it is less than or equal to (≤) are called *min-heaps*.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Binary heaps are also commonly employed in the heapsort sorting algorithm, which is an in-place algorithm as binary heaps can be implemented as an implicit data structure, storing keys in an array and using their relative positions within that array to represent child–parent relationships.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Both the insert and remove operations modify the heap to preserve the shape property first, by adding or removing from the end of the heap.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Then the heap property is restored by traversing up or down the heap.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Compare the added element with its parent; if they are in the correct order, stop.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] If not, swap the element with its parent and return to the previous step.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Steps 2 and 3, which restore the heap property by comparing and possibly swapping a node with its parent, are called *the up-heap* operation (also known as *bubble-up*, *percolate-up*, *sift-up*, *trickle-up*, *swim-up*, *heapify-up*, *cascade-up*, or *fix-up*).
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The number of operations required depends only on the number of levels the new element must rise to satisfy the heap property.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Thus, the insertion operation has a worst-case time complexity of O(log *n*).
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] For a random heap, and for repeated insertions, the insertion operation has an average-case complexity of O(1).
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The following animation depicts an example of binary heap insertion.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] It begins by inserting 15 into the heap at the left-most empty entry on the next available row.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] However, the heap property is violated since 15 > 8, so we need to swap the 15 and the 8.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Even after this swap, the heap property is still violated since 15 > 11, so we need to swap again.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The heap property is now satisfied, so the resulting binary tree is a valid max-heap.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Compare the new root with its children; if they are in the correct order, stop.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] If not, swap the element with one of its children and return to the previous step.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] So, if we have the same max-heap as before, we remove the 11 and replace it with the 4.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Now the heap property is violated since 8 is greater than 4.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] In this case, swapping the two elements, 4 and 8, is enough to restore the heap property and we need not swap elements further.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The downward-moving node is swapped with the *larger* of its children in a max-heap (in a min-heap it would be swapped with its smaller child), until it satisfies the heap property in its new position.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] This functionality is achieved by the **Max-Heapify** function as defined below in pseudocode for an array-backed heap *A* of length *length*(*A*).
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] For the above algorithm to correctly re-heapify the array, no nodes besides the node at index *i* and its two direct children can violate the heap property.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The down-heap operation (without the preceding swap) can also be used to modify the value of the root, even when an element is not being deleted.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] In the worst case, the new root has to be swapped with its child on each level until it reaches the bottom level of the heap, meaning that the delete operation has a time complexity relative to the height of the tree, or O(log *n*).
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Inserting an element then extracting from the heap can be done more efficiently than simply calling the insert and extract functions defined above, which would involve both an `upheap` and `downheap` operation.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Python provides such a function for insertion then extraction called "heappushpop", which is paraphrased below.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The heap array is assumed to have its first element at index 1.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Finding an arbitrary element takes O(n) time.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] This can be easily proved by considering that the heap is not sorted so we need to look through the whole tree to find the target element.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Swap this element with the last element.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Down-heapify or up-heapify to restore the heap property.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] In a max-heap (min-heap), up-heapify is only required when the new key of element i is greater (smaller) than the previous one because only the heap-property of the parent element might be violated.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Assuming that the heap-property was valid between element i and its children before the element swap, it can't be violated by a now larger (smaller) key value.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] When the new key is less (greater) than the previous one then only a down-heapify is required because the heap-property might only be violated in the child elements.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The decrease key operation replaces the value of a node with a given value with a lower value, and the increase key operation does the same but with a higher value.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] This involves finding the node with the given value, changing the value, and then down-heapifying or up-heapifying to restore the heap property.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Building a heap from an array of n input elements can be done by starting with an empty heap, then successively inserting each element.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] This approach, called Williams' method after the inventor of binary heaps, is easily seen to run in *O*(*n* log *n*) time: it performs n insertions at *O*(log *n*) cost each.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] However, Williams' method is suboptimal.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] A faster method (due to Floyd) starts by arbitrarily putting the elements on a binary tree, respecting the shape property (the tree could be represented by an array, see below).
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Then starting from the lowest level and moving upwards, sift the root of each subtree downward as in the deletion algorithm until the heap property is restored.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] This process takes $O(h)$ operations (swaps) per node.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] In this method most of the heapification takes place in the lower levels.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Since the height of the heap is $\lfloor \log n\rfloor$ , the number of nodes at height h is $\leq {\frac {2^{\lfloor \log n\rfloor }}{2^{h}}}\leq {\frac {n}{2^{h}}}$ .
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] This uses the fact that the given infinite series ${\textstyle \sum _{i=0}^{\infty }i/2^{i}}$ converges.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] where *s*2(*n*) is the sum of all digits of the binary representation of n and *e*2(*n*) is the exponent of 2 in the prime factorization of n.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The average case is more complex to analyze, but it can be shown to asymptotically approach 1.8814 *n* − 2 log2*n* + *O*(1) comparisons.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The **Build-Max-Heap** function that follows, converts an array *A* which stores a complete binary tree with *n* nodes to a max-heap by repeatedly using **Max-Heapify** (down-heapify for a max-heap) in a bottom-up manner.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The array elements indexed by *floor*(*n*/2) + 1, *floor*(*n*/2) + 2, ..., *n* are all leaves for the tree (assuming that indices start at 1)—thus each is a one-element heap, and does not need to be down-heapified.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] **Build-Max-Heap** runs **Max-Heapify** on each of the remaining tree nodes.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Heaps are commonly implemented with an array.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Any binary tree can be stored in an array, but because a binary heap is always a complete binary tree, it can be stored compactly.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] No space is required for pointers; instead, the parent and children of each node can be found by arithmetic on array indices.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] These properties make this heap implementation a simple example of an implicit data structure or Ahnentafel list.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Details depend on the root position, which in turn may depend on constraints of a programming language used for implementation, or programmer preference.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Specifically, sometimes the root is placed at index 1, in order to simplify arithmetic.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Let *n* be the number of elements in the heap and *i* be an arbitrary valid index of the array storing the heap.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] This implementation is used in the heapsort algorithm which reuses the space allocated to the input array to store the heap (i.e. the algorithm is done in-place).
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] This implementation is also useful as a Priority queue.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] When a dynamic array is used, insertion of an unbounded number of items is possible.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The `upheap` or `downheap` operations can then be stated in terms of an array as follows: suppose that the heap property holds for the indices *b*, *b*+1, ..., *e*.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The sift-down function extends the heap property to *b*−1, *b*, *b*+1, ..., *e*.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Only index *i* = *b*−1 can violate the heap property.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Let *j* be the index of the largest child of *a*[*i*] (for a max-heap, or the smallest child for a min-heap) within the range *b*, ..., *e*.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] (If no such index exists because 2*i* > *e* then the heap property holds for the newly extended range and nothing needs to be done.) By swapping the values *a*[*i*] and *a*[*j*] the heap property for position *i* is established.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] At this point, the only problem is that the heap property might not hold for index *j*.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The sift-down function is applied tail-recursively to index *j* until the heap property is established for all elements.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] In each step it only needs two comparisons and one swap.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The index value where it is working doubles in each iteration, so that at most log2 *e* steps are required.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] For big heaps and using virtual memory, storing elements in an array according to the above scheme is inefficient: (almost) every level is in a different page.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] B-heaps are binary heaps that keep subtrees in a single page, reducing the number of pages accessed by up to a factor of ten.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The operation of merging two binary heaps takes Θ(*n*) for equal-sized heaps.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The best you can do is (in case of array implementation) simply concatenating the two heap arrays and build a heap of the result.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] A heap on *n* elements can be merged with a heap on *k* elements using O(log *n* log *k*) key comparisons, or, in case of a pointer-based implementation, in O(log *n* log *k*) time.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] An algorithm for splitting a heap on *n* elements into two heaps on *k* and *n-k* elements, respectively, based on a new view of heaps as an ordered collections of subheaps was presented in.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The algorithm requires O(log *n* * log *n*) comparisons.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The view also presents a new and conceptually simple algorithm for merging heaps.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] When merging is a common task, a different heap implementation is recommended, such as binomial heaps, which can be merged in O(log *n*).
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Additionally, a binary heap can be implemented with a traditional binary tree data structure, but there is an issue with finding the adjacent element on the last level on the binary heap when adding an element.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] This element can be determined algorithmically or by adding extra data to the nodes, called "threading" the tree—instead of merely storing references to the children, we store the inorder successor of the node as well.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] It is possible to modify the heap structure to make the extraction of both the smallest and largest element possible in O $(\log n)$ time.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] To do this, the rows alternate between min heap and max-heap.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The algorithms are roughly the same, but, in each step, one must consider the alternating rows with alternating comparisons.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The performance is roughly the same as a normal single direction heap.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] This idea can be generalized to a min-max-median heap.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] In an array-based heap, the children and parent of a node can be located via simple arithmetic on the node's index.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] This section derives the relevant equations for heaps with their root at index 0, with additional notes on heaps with their root at index 1.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] To avoid confusion, we define the **level** of a node as its distance from the root, such that the root itself occupies level 0.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] For a general node located at index i (beginning from 0), we will first derive the index of its right child, ${\text{right}}=2i+2$ .
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Let node i be located in level L, and note that any level l contains exactly $2^{l}$ nodes.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Furthermore, there are exactly $2^{l+1}-1$ nodes contained in the layers up to and including layer l (think of binary arithmetic; 0111...111 = 1000...000 - 1).
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Because the root is stored at 0, the kth node will be stored at index $(k-1)$ .
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Putting these observations together yields the following expression for the **index of the last node in layer l**.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Each of these j nodes must have exactly 2 children, so there must be $2j$ nodes separating i's right child from the end of its layer ( $L+1$ ).
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Noting that the left child of any node is always 1 place before its right child, we get ${\text{left}}=2i+1$ .
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] If the root is located at index 1 instead of 0, the last node in each level is instead at index $2^{l+1}-1$ .
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Using this throughout yields ${\text{left}}=2i$ and ${\text{right}}=2i+1$ for heaps with their root at 1.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Now consider the expression $\left\lfloor {\dfrac {i-1}{2}}\right\rfloor$ .
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] If node i is a left child, this gives the result immediately, however, it also gives the correct result if node i is a right child.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] In this case, $(i-2)$ must be even, and hence $(i-1)$ must be odd.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Since the ordering of siblings in a heap is not specified by the heap property, a single node's two children can be freely interchanged unless doing so violates the shape property (compare with treap).
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Note, however, that in the common array-based heap, simply swapping the children might also necessitate moving the children's sub-tree nodes to retain the heap property.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The binary heap is a special case of the d-ary heap in which d = 2.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Here are time complexities of various heap data structures.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The abbreviation am. indicates that the given complexity is amortized, otherwise it is a worst-case complexity.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] For the meaning of "*O*(*f*)" and "*Θ*(*f*)" see Big O notation.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] This does not mean that *sorting* can be done in linear time since building a heap is only the first step of the heapsort algorithm.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] *make-heap* is the operation of building a heap from a sequence of *n* unsorted elements.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] It can be done in *Θ*(*n*) time whenever *meld* runs in *O*(log *n*) time (where both complexities can be amortized).
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Another algorithm achieves *Θ*(*n*) for binary heaps.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] For persistent heaps (not supporting *decrease-key*), a generic transformation reduces the cost of *meld* to that of *insert*, while the new cost of *delete-min* is the sum of the old costs of *delete-min* and *meld*.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Here, it makes *meld* run in *Θ*(1) time (amortized, if the cost of *insert* is) while *delete-min* still runs in *O*(log *n*).
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Applied to skew binomial heaps, it yields Brodal-Okasaki queues, persistent heaps with optimal worst-case complexities.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] Brodal queues and strict Fibonacci heaps achieve optimal worst-case complexities for heaps.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] They were first described as imperative data structures.
[src:binary-heap/binary-heap] The Brodal-Okasaki queue is a persistent data structure achieving the same optimum, except that *decrease-key* is not supported.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] The ***d*-ary heap** or ***d*-heap** is a priority queue data structure, a generalization of the binary heap in which the nodes have *d* children instead of 2.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] Thus, a binary heap is a 2-heap, and a **ternary heap** is a 3-heap.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] According to Tarjan and Jensen et al., *d*-ary heaps were invented by Donald B.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] This data structure allows decrease priority operations to be performed more quickly than binary heaps, at the expense of slower delete minimum operations.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] This tradeoff leads to better running times for algorithms such as Dijkstra's algorithm in which decrease priority operations are more common than delete min operations.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] Additionally, *d*-ary heaps have better memory cache behavior than binary heaps, allowing them to run more quickly in practice despite having a theoretically larger worst-case running time.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] Like binary heaps, *d*-ary heaps are an in-place data structure that use no additional storage beyond that needed to store the array of items in the heap.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] The *d*-ary heap consists of an array of *n* items, each of which has a priority associated with it.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] Thus, the parent of the item at position *i* (for any *i* > 0) is the item at position ⌊(*i* − 1)/*d*⌋ and its children are the items at positions *di* + 1 through *di* + *d*.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] According to the heap property, in a min-heap, each item has a priority that is at least as large as its parent; in a max-heap, each item has a priority that is no larger than its parent.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] The minimum priority item in a min-heap (or the maximum priority item in a max-heap) may always be found at position 0 of the array.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] To remove this item from the priority queue, the last item *x* in the array is moved into its place, and the length of the array is decreased by one.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] The same downward swapping procedure may be used to increase the priority of an item in a min-heap, or to decrease the priority of an item in a max-heap.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] To insert a new item into the heap, the item is appended to the end of the array, and then while the heap property is violated it is swapped with its parent, moving it upward in the tree and earlier in the array, until eventually the heap property is satisfied.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] The same upward-swapping procedure may be used to decrease the priority of an item in a min-heap, or to increase the priority of an item in a max-heap.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] To create a new heap from an array of *n* items, one may loop over the items in reverse order, starting from the item at position *n* − 1 and ending at the item at position 0, applying the downward-swapping procedure for each item.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] In a *d*-ary heap containing *n* items, both the upward-swapping procedure and the downward-swapping procedure may perform as many as log*d* *n* = log *n* / log *d* swaps.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] In the upward-swapping procedure, each swap involves a single comparison of an item with its parent, and takes constant time.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] Therefore, the time to insert a new item into the heap, to decrease the priority of an item in a min-heap, or to increase the priority of an item in a max-heap, is O(log *n* / log *d*).
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] In the downward-swapping procedure, each swap involves *d* comparisons and takes O(*d*) time: it takes *d* − 1 comparisons to determine the minimum or maximum of the children and then one more comparison against the parent to determine whether a swap is needed.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] Therefore, the time to delete the root item, to increase the priority of an item in a min-heap, or to decrease the priority of an item in a max-heap, is O(*d* log *n* / log *d*).
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] When creating a *d*-ary heap from a set of *n* items, most of the items are in positions that will eventually hold leaves of the *d*-ary tree, and no downward swapping is performed for those items.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] At most *n*/*d* + 1 items are non-leaves, and may be swapped downwards at least once, at a cost of O(*d*) time to find the child to swap them with.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] At most *n*/*d*2 + 1 nodes may be swapped downward two times, incurring an additional O(*d*) cost for the second swap beyond the cost already counted in the first term, etc.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] where sd(n) is the sum of all digits of the standard base-d representation of n and ed(n) is the exponent of d in the factorization of n.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] The space usage of the *d*-ary heap, with insert and delete-min operations, is linear, as it uses no extra storage other than an array containing a list of the items in the heap.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] If changes to the priorities of existing items need to be supported, then one must also maintain pointers from the items to their positions in the heap, which again uses only linear storage.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] When operating on a graph with m edges and n vertices, both Dijkstra's algorithm for shortest paths and Prim's algorithm for minimum spanning trees use a min-heap in which there are *n* delete-min operations and as many as m decrease-priority operations.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] An alternative priority queue data structure, the Fibonacci heap, gives an even better theoretical running time of O(*m* + *n* log *n*), but in practice d-ary heaps are generally at least as fast, and often faster, than Fibonacci heaps for this application.
[src:binary-heap/d-ary-heap] 4-heaps may perform better than binary heaps in practice, even for delete-min operations.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] In computer science, a **heap** is a tree-based data structure that satisfies the **heap property**: In a *max heap*, for any given node C, if P is the parent node of C, then the *key* (the *value*) of P is greater than or equal to the key of C.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] In a *min heap*, the key of P is less than or equal to the key of C.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] The node at the "top" of the heap (with no parents) is called the *root* node.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] The heap is one maximally efficient implementation of an abstract data type called a priority queue, and in fact, priority queues are often referred to as "heaps", regardless of how they may be implemented.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] In a heap, the highest (or lowest) priority element is always stored at the root.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] However, a heap is not a sorted structure; it can be regarded as being partially ordered.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] A heap is a useful data structure when it is necessary to repeatedly remove the object with the highest (or lowest) priority, or when insertions need to be interspersed with removals of the root node.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] A common implementation of a heap is the binary heap, in which the tree is a complete binary tree (see figure).
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] The heap data structure, specifically the binary heap, was introduced by J.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] Williams in 1964, as a data structure for the heapsort sorting algorithm.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] Heaps are also crucial in several efficient graph algorithms such as Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] When a heap is a complete binary tree, it has the smallest possible height—a heap with *N* nodes and *a* branches for each node always has log*a* *N* height.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] Note that, as shown in the graphic, there is no implied ordering between siblings or cousins and no implied sequence for an in-order traversal (as there would be in, e.g., a binary search tree).
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] The heap relation mentioned above applies only between nodes and their parents, grandparents.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] The maximum number of children each node can have depends on the type of heap.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] Heaps are typically constructed in-place in the same array where the elements are stored, with their structure being implicit in the access pattern of the operations.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] Heaps differ in this way from other data structures with similar or in some cases better theoretic bounds such as radix trees in that they require no additional memory beyond that used for storing the keys.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] For a binary heap, in the array, the first index contains the root element.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] The next two indices of the array contain the root's children.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] The next four indices contain the four children of the root's two child nodes, and so on.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] Therefore, given a node at index i, its children are at indices ⁠ $2i+1$ ⁠ and ⁠ $2i+2$ ⁠, and its parent is at index ⌊(*i*−1)/2⌋ in an array starting from index ⁠ 0 ⁠, or at ⁠ $2i$ ⁠, ⁠ $2i+1$ ⁠, and ⌊*i*/2⌋, respectively, in an array starting from ⁠ 1 ⁠.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] This simple indexing scheme makes it efficient to walk "up" or "down" the tree.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] Balancing a heap is done by sift-up or sift-down operations (swapping elements which are out of order).
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] As we can build a heap from an array without requiring extra memory (for the nodes, for example), heapsort can be used to sort an array in-place.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] After an element is inserted into or deleted from a heap, the heap property may be violated, and the heap must be re-balanced by swapping elements within the array.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] This is faster than a sequence of consecutive insertions into an originally empty heap, which is log-linear.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] For persistent heaps (not supporting *increase-key*), a generic transformation reduces the cost of *meld* to that of *insert*, while the new cost of *delete-max* is the sum of the old costs of *delete-max* and *meld*.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] Here, it makes *meld* run in *Θ*(1) time (amortized, if the cost of *insert* is) while *delete-max* still runs in *O*(log *n*).
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] The Brodal-Okasaki queue is a persistent data structure achieving the same optimum, except that *increase-key* is not supported.
[src:binary-heap/heap-data-structure] The heap data structure has many applications.
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] In computer science, an **implicit data structure** or **space-efficient data structure** is a data structure that stores very little information other than the main or required data: a data structure that requires low overhead.
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] They are called "implicit" because the position of the elements carries meaning and relationship between elements; this is contrasted with the use of pointers to give an *explicit* relationship between elements.
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] Definitions of "low overhead" vary, but generally means constant overhead; in big O notation, *O*(1) overhead.
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] A less restrictive definition is a succinct data structure, which allows greater overhead.
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] An implicit data structure is one with constant *O*(1) space overhead (above the information-theoretic lower bound).
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] This latter definition is today more standard, and the still-looser notion of a data structure with non-constant but small *o*(*n*) overhead is today known as a succinct data structure, as defined by Jacobson (1988); it was referred to as **semi-implicit** by Munro & Suwanda (1980).
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] A fundamental distinction is between *static* data structures (read-only) and *dynamic* data structures (which can be modified).
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] Simple implicit data structures, such as representing a sorted list as an array, may be very efficient as a static data structure, but inefficient as a dynamic data structure, due to modification operations (such as insertion in the case of a sorted list) being inefficient.
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] Similarly, a *null-terminated string* is an implicit data structure for a string (list of characters).
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] These are considered very simple because they are static data structures (read-only), and only admit the simple operation of iteration over the elements.
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] Similarly simple is representing a multi-dimensional array as a single 1-dimensional array, together with its dimensions.
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] For example, representing an *m* × *n* array as a single list of length *m·n*, together with the numbers *m* and *n* (instead of as a 1-dimensional array of pointers to each 1-dimensional subarray).
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] The elements need not be of the same type, and a table of data (a list of records) may similarly be represented implicitly as a flat (1-dimensional) list, together with the length of each field, so long as each field has uniform size (so a single size can be used per field, not per record).
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] A less trivial example is representing a sorted list by a *sorted array*, which allows search in logarithmic time by binary search.
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] Contrast with a search tree, specifically a binary search tree, which also allows logarithmic-time search, but requires pointers.
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] A sorted array is only efficient as a static data structure, as modifying the list is slow – unlike a binary search tree – but does not require the space overhead of a tree.
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] An important example of an implicit data structure is representing a perfect binary tree as a list, in increasing order of depth, so root, first left child, first right child, first left child of first left child, etc.
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] Such a tree occurs notably for an ancestry chart to a given depth, and the implicit representation is known as an *Ahnentafel* (ancestor table).
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] This can be generalized to a complete binary tree (where the last level may be incomplete), which yields the best-known example of an implicit data structure, namely the *binary heap*, which is an implicit data structure for a priority queue.
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] This is more sophisticated than earlier examples because it allows multiple operations, and is an efficient *dynamic* data structure (it allows efficient modification of the data): not only **top**, but also **insert** and **pop**.
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] More sophisticated implicit data structures include the beap (bi-parental heap).
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] The trivial examples of lists or tables of values date to prehistory, while historically non-trivial implicit data structures date at least to the Ahnentafel, which was introduced by Michaël Eytzinger in 1590 for use in genealogy.
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] In formal computer science, the first implicit data structure is generally considered to be the sorted list, used for binary search, which was introduced by John Mauchly in 1946, in the Moore School Lectures, the first ever set of lectures regarding any computer-related topic.
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] The binary heap was introduced in Williams (1964) to implement the heapsort.
[src:binary-heap/implicit-data-structure] The notion of an implicit data structure was formalized in Munro & Suwanda (1980), as part of introducing and analyzing the beap.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] In computer science, a **min-max heap** is a complete binary tree data structure which combines the usefulness of both a min-heap and a max-heap, that is, it provides constant time retrieval and logarithmic time removal of both the minimum and maximum elements in it.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] This makes the min-max heap a very useful data structure to implement a double-ended priority queue.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] Like binary min-heaps and max-heaps, min-max heaps support logarithmic insertion and deletion and can be built in linear time.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] Min-max heaps are often represented implicitly in an *array*; hence it's referred to as an implicit data structure.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] The *min-max heap* property is: *each node at an even level in the tree is less than all of its descendants, while each node at an odd level in the tree is greater than all of its descendants*.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] These last two operations can be implemented in constant and logarithmic time, respectively.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] The notion of min-max ordering can be extended to other structures based on the max- or min-ordering, such as leftist trees, generating a new (and more powerful) class of data structures.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] A min-max heap can also be useful when implementing an external quicksort.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] A *max-min heap* is defined analogously; in such a heap, the maximum value is stored at the root, and the smallest value is stored at one of the root's children.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] In the following operations we assume that the min-max heap is represented in an array `A[1..N]`; The $ith$ location in the array will correspond to a node located on the level $\lfloor \log _{2}i\rfloor$ in the heap.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] Creating a min-max heap is accomplished by an adaptation of Floyd's linear-time heap construction algorithm, which proceeds in a bottom-up fashion.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] In this function, *h* is the initial array, whose elements may not be ordered according to the min-max heap property.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] The `push-down` operation (which sometimes is also called *heapify*) of a min-max heap is explained next.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] The algorithm for `push-down-max` is identical to that for push-down-min, but with all of the comparison operators reversed.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] The path from the new node to the root (considering only min (max) levels) should be in a descending (ascending) order as it was before the insertion.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] So, we need to make a binary insertion of the new node into this sequence.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] Technically it is simpler to swap the new node with its parent while the parent is greater (less).
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] This process is implemented by calling the `push-up` algorithm described below on the index of the newly-appended key.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] Here is one example for inserting an element to a Min-Max Heap.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] Say we have the following min-max heap and want to insert a new node with value 6.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] Initially, node 6 is inserted as a right child of the node 11.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] 6 is less than 11, therefore it is less than all the nodes on the max levels (41), and we need to check only the min levels (8 and 11).
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] We should swap the nodes 6 and 11 and then swap 6 and 8.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] So, 6 gets moved to the root position of the heap, the former root 8 gets moved down to replace 11, and 11 becomes a right child of 8.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] Consider adding the new node 81 instead of 6.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] Initially, the node is inserted as a right child of the node 11.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] 81 is greater than 11, therefore it is greater than any node on any of the min levels (8 and 11).
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] Now, we only need to check the nodes on the max levels (41) and make one swap.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] The minimum node (or a minimum node in the case of duplicate keys) of a Min-Max Heap is always located at the root.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] Find Minimum is thus a trivial constant time operation which simply returns the roots.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] The maximum node (or a maximum node in the case of duplicate keys) of a Min-Max Heap that contains more than one node is always located on the first max level--i.e., as one of the immediate children of the root.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] Find Maximum thus requires at most one comparison, to determine which of the two children of the root is larger, and as such is also a constant time operation.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] If the Min-Max heap contains one node then that node is the maximum node.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] Removing the minimum is just a special case of removing an arbitrary node whose index in the array is known.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] In this case, the last element of the array is removed (reducing the length of the array) and used to replace the root, at the head of the array.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] `push-down` is then called on the root index to restore the heap property in $O(\log _{2}(n))$ time.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] Removing the maximum is again a special case of removing an arbitrary node with known index.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] As in the Find Maximum operation, a single comparison is required to identify the maximal child of the root, after which it is replaced with the final element of the array and `push-down` is then called on the index of the replaced maximum to restore the heap property.
[src:binary-heap/min-max-heap] The min-max-median heap is a variant of the min-max heap, suggested in the original publication on the structure, that supports the operations of an order statistic tree.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] In computer science, a **priority queue** is an abstract data type similar to a regular queue where each element has an associated priority determining its order of service.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Priority queue serves highest priority items first.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Priority values have to be instances of an ordered data type, and higher priority can be given either to the lesser or to the greater values with respect to the given order relation.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] For example, in the Java standard library, the PriorityQueue class considers the lowest element with respect to their order as having the highest priority.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] While priority queues are often implemented using heaps, they are conceptually distinct.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] A priority queue can be implemented with a heap or with other methods; just as a list can be implemented with a linked list or with an array.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Stacks and queues can be implemented as particular kinds of priority queues, with the priority determined by the order in which the elements are inserted.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] In a stack, the priority of each inserted element is monotonically increasing; thus, the last element inserted is always the first retrieved.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] In a queue, the priority of each inserted element is monotonically decreasing; thus, the first element inserted is always the first retrieved.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] In some implementations, if two elements have the same priority, they are served in the same order in which they were enqueued.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] In other implementations, the order of elements with the same priority is undefined.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] One can create a simple, but inefficient priority queue in a number of ways.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] These naive implementations can demonstrate the expected behaviour of a priority queue in a simpler manner.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] To improve performance, priority queues are typically based on a heap, giving $O(\log n)$ performance for inserts and removals, and $O(n)$ to build the heap initially from a set of n elements.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Variants of the basic heap data structure such as pairing heaps or Fibonacci heaps can provide better bounds for some operations.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] From a space-complexity standpoint, using self-balancing binary search tree with linked list takes more storage, since it requires storing extra references to other nodes.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] From a computational-complexity standpoint, priority queues are congruent to sorting algorithms.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The section on the equivalence of priority queues and sorting algorithms, below, describes how efficient sorting algorithms can create efficient priority queues.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] There are several specialized heap data structures that either supply additional operations or outperform heap-based implementations for specific types of keys, specifically integer keys.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] For applications that do many "peek" operations for every "`extract-min`" operation, the time complexity for peek actions can be reduced to $O(1)$ in all tree and heap implementations by caching the highest priority element after every insertion and removal.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] For insertion, this adds at most a constant cost, since the newly inserted element is compared only to the previously cached minimum element.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] For deletion, this at most adds an additional "peek" cost, which is typically cheaper than the deletion cost, so overall time complexity is not significantly impacted.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Monotone priority queues are specialized queues that are optimized for the case where no item is ever inserted that has a lower priority (in the case of min-heap) than any item previously extracted.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] This restriction is met by several practical applications of priority queues.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The semantics of priority queues naturally suggest a sorting method: insert all the elements to be sorted into a priority queue, and sequentially remove them; they will come out in sorted order.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] This is actually the procedure used by several sorting algorithms, once the layer of abstraction provided by the priority queue is removed.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] A sorting algorithm can also be used to implement a priority queue.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] For example, if one has an $O(n\log n)$ sort algorithm, one can create a priority queue with $O(1)$ pulling and $O(\log n)$ insertion.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] A priority queue is often considered to be a "container data structure".
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The Standard Template Library (STL), and the C++ 1998 standard, specifies std::priority_queue as one of the STL container adaptor class templates.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] However, it does not specify how two elements with same priority should be served, and indeed, common implementations will not return them according to their order in the queue.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Unlike actual STL containers, it does not allow iteration of its elements (it strictly adheres to its abstract data type definition).
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] STL also has utility functions for manipulating another random-access container as a binary max-heap.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The Boost libraries also have an implementation in the library heap.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Python's heapq module implements a binary min-heap on top of a list.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Java's library contains a `PriorityQueue` (`java.util.PriorityQueue`) class, which implements a min-priority-queue as a binary heap.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] .NET's library contains a System.Collections.Generic.PriorityQueue class, which implements an array-backed, quaternary min-heap.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Scala's library contains a scala.collection.mutable.PriorityQueue class, which implements a max-priority-queue.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Go's library contains a container/heap module, which implements a min-heap on top of any compatible data structure.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Rust's standard library contains a std::collections::BinaryHeap struct, which implements a priority queue with a binary heap.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The Standard PHP Library extension contains the class SplPriorityQueue.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Apple's Core Foundation framework contains a CFBinaryHeap structure, which implements a min-heap.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Priority queuing can be used to manage limited resources such as bandwidth on a transmission line from a network router.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] In the event of outgoing traffic queuing due to insufficient bandwidth, all other queues can be halted to send the traffic from the highest priority queue upon arrival.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] This ensures that the prioritized traffic (such as real-time traffic, e.g. an RTP stream of a VoIP connection) is forwarded with the least delay and the least likelihood of being rejected due to a queue reaching its maximum capacity.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] All other traffic can be handled when the highest priority queue is empty.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Another approach used is to send disproportionately more traffic from higher priority queues.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Many modern protocols for local area networks also include the concept of priority queues at the media access control (MAC) sub-layer to ensure that high-priority applications (such as VoIP or IPTV) experience lower latency than other applications which can be served with best-effort service.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Examples include IEEE 802.11e (an amendment to IEEE 802.11 which provides quality of service) and ITU-T G.hn (a standard for high-speed local area network using existing home wiring (power lines, phone lines and coaxial cables).
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Usually a limitation (policer) is set to limit the bandwidth that traffic from the highest priority queue can take, in order to prevent high priority packets from choking off all other traffic.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] This limit is usually never reached due to high level control instances such as the Cisco Callmanager, which can be programmed to inhibit calls which would exceed the programmed bandwidth limit.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Another use of a priority queue is to manage the events in a discrete event simulation.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The events are added to the queue with their simulation time used as the priority.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The execution of the simulation proceeds by repeatedly pulling the top of the queue and executing the event thereon.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] When the graph is stored in the form of adjacency list or matrix, priority queue can be used to extract minimum efficiently when implementing Dijkstra's algorithm, although one also needs the ability to alter the priority of a particular vertex in the priority queue efficiently.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] If instead, a graph is stored as node objects, and priority-node pairs are inserted into a heap, altering the priority of a particular vertex is not necessary if one tracks visited nodes.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Once a node is visited, if it comes up in the heap again (having had a lower priority number associated with it earlier), it is popped-off and ignored.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Huffman coding requires one to repeatedly obtain the two lowest-frequency trees.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] A priority queue is one method of doing this.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Best-first search algorithms, like the A* search algorithm, find the shortest path between two vertices or nodes of a weighted graph, trying out the most promising routes first.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] A priority queue (also known as the *fringe*) is used to keep track of unexplored routes; the one for which the estimate (a lower bound in the case of A*) of the total path length is smallest is given highest priority.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] If memory limitations make best-first search impractical, variants like the SMA* algorithm can be used instead, with a double-ended priority queue to allow removal of low-priority items.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The Real-time Optimally Adapting Meshes (ROAM) algorithm computes a dynamically changing triangulation of a terrain.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] It works by splitting triangles where more detail is needed and merging them where less detail is needed.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The algorithm assigns each triangle in the terrain a priority, usually related to the error decrease if that triangle would be split.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The algorithm uses two priority queues, one for triangles that can be split and another for triangles that can be merged.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] In each step the triangle from the split queue with the highest priority is split, or the triangle from the merge queue with the lowest priority is merged with its neighbours.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Using min heap priority queue in Prim's algorithm to find the minimum spanning tree of a connected and undirected graph, one can achieve a good running time.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] This min heap priority queue uses the min heap data structure which supports operations such as `insert`, `minimum`, `extract-min`, `decrease-key`.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] In this implementation, the weight of the edges is used to decide the priority of the vertices.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Lower the weight, higher the priority and higher the weight, lower the priority.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Parallelization can be used to speed up priority queues, but requires some changes to the priority queue interface.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The reason for such changes is that a sequential update usually only has ${\textstyle O(1)}$ or ${\textstyle O(\log n)}$ cost, and there is no practical gain to parallelize such an operation.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] One possible change is to allow the concurrent access of multiple processors to the same priority queue.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The second possible change is to allow batch operations that work on ${\textstyle k}$ elements, instead of just one element.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] For example, `extractMin` will remove the first ${\textstyle k}$ elements with the highest priority.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] If the priority queue allows concurrent access, multiple processes can perform operations concurrently on that priority queue.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] First of all, the definition of the semantics of the individual operations is no longer obvious.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] For example, if two processes want to extract the element with the highest priority, should they get the same element or different ones?
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] This restricts parallelism on the level of the program using the priority queue.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] In addition, because multiple processes have access to the same element, this leads to contention.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The concurrent access to a priority queue can be implemented on a Concurrent Read, Concurrent Write (CRCW) PRAM model.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] In the following the priority queue is implemented as a skip list.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] In addition, an atomic synchronization primitive, CAS, is used to make the skip list lock-free.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The nodes of the skip list consists of a unique key, a priority, an array of pointers, for each level, to the next nodes and a `delete` mark.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The `delete` mark marks if the node is about to be deleted by a process.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] This ensures that other processes can react to the deletion appropriately.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] If the concurrent access to a priority queue is allowed, conflicts may arise between two processes.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] For example, a conflict arises if one process is trying to insert a new node, but at the same time another process is about to delete the predecessor of that node.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] There is a risk that the new node is added to the skip list, yet it is not longer reachable.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] In this setting, operations on a priority queue is generalized to a batch of ${\textstyle k}$ elements.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] For instance, `k_extract-min` deletes the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements of the priority queue and returns those.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] In a shared-memory setting, the parallel priority queue can be easily implemented using parallel binary search trees and join-based tree algorithms.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] In particular, `k_extract-min` corresponds to a *split* on the binary search tree that has ${\textstyle O(\log n)}$ cost and yields a tree that contains the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] `k_insert` can be applied by a *union* of the original priority queue and the batch of insertions.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] If the batch is already sorted by the key, `k_insert` has ${\textstyle O(k\log(1+{\frac {n}{k}}))}$ cost.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Otherwise, we need to first sort the batch, so the cost will be ${\textstyle O(k\log(1+{\frac {n}{k}})+k\log k)=O(k\log n)}$ .
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Other operations for priority queue can be applied similarly.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] For instance, `k_decrease-key` can be done by first applying `difference` and then `union`, which first deletes the elements and then inserts them back with the updated keys.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] All these operations are highly parallel, and the theoretical and practical efficiency can be found in related research papers.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The rest of this section discusses a queue-based algorithm on distributed memory.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] We assume each processor has its own local memory and a local (sequential) priority queue.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The elements of the global (parallel) priority queue are distributed across all processors.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] A `k_insert` operation assigns the elements uniformly random to the processors which insert the elements into their local queues.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Note that single elements can still be inserted into the queue.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Using this strategy the global smallest elements are in the union of the local smallest elements of every processor with high probability.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Thus each processor holds a representative part of the global priority queue.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] This property is used when `k_extract-min` is executed, as the smallest ${\textstyle m}$ elements of each local queue are removed and collected in a result set.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The elements in the result set are still associated with their original processor.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The number of elements ${\textstyle m}$ that is removed from each local queue depends on ${\textstyle k}$ and the number of processors ${\textstyle p}$ .
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] By parallel selection the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements of the result set are determined.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] With high probability these are the global ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] If not, ${\textstyle m}$ elements are again removed from each local queue and put into the result set.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] This is done until the global ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements are in the result set.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Now these ${\textstyle k}$ elements can be returned.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] All other elements of the result set are inserted back into their local queues.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The running time of `k_extract-min` is expected ${\textstyle O({\frac {k}{p}}\log(n))}$ , where ${\textstyle k=\Omega (p\cdot \log(p))}$ and ${\textstyle n}$ is the size of the priority queue.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The priority queue can be further improved by not moving the remaining elements of the result set directly back into the local queues after a `k_extract-min` operation.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] This saves moving elements back and forth all the time between the result set and the local queues.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] By removing several elements at once a considerable speedup can be reached.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] But not all algorithms can use this kind of priority queue.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] Dijkstra's algorithm for example can not work on several nodes at once.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] The algorithm takes the node with the smallest distance from the priority queue and calculates new distances for all its neighbor nodes.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] If you would take out ${\textstyle k}$ nodes, working at one node could change the distance of another one of the ${\textstyle k}$ nodes.
[src:binary-heap/priority-queue] So using k-element operations destroys the label setting property of Dijkstra's algorithm.
